Note:
EXPRESSION LOWERING - HIR Expressions to MIR Instructions (P2-E Group B)

Post-order handlers for HIR expression nodes (10000-10999). Each handler
reads its children's MIR value ids off the LoweringContext result stack
(children have already been lowered by the visitor), emits the MIR
instruction for the current node via the MIR builder context, and pushes
the result value id back onto the result stack for the parent handler.

Per the v3 design Section 3.4 table, expressions use only post hooks
(pre is null) with two exceptions:
  - HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION uses pre + post to record the argument count
    target before children are visited and consume them in post.

Helper procs:
  - map_binary_operator_to_mir_opcode: HIR operator id -> MIR opcode
  - map_unary_operator_to_mir_opcode: HIR unary operator id -> MIR opcode

Registration:
  - register_expression_handlers installs every expression handler in
    the dispatch table.
:End Note

Note: ============================================================
Note: IMPORTS
Note: ============================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir.runa" as MIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir_nodes.runa" as MIRNodes
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/lowering/lowering_context.runa" as LCtx
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir_builder.runa" as MIRBuilder
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================
Note: HIR Operator Mappings
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
Maps a HIR binary operator id (0-based small integer assigned by HIR
construction) to the corresponding MIR opcode (20000+ namespace).
Centralising this mapping keeps the lowering handler free of magic
numbers and gives the optimiser a single point to extend with new
operators (e.g., saturating arithmetic, wrapping arithmetic) without
touching the dispatcher.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Linear if-cascade keyed by the HIR_OP_* constants defined in HIR
(currently inline integers, to be promoted to named constants in a
separate task). Returns MIR_NOP for unrecognised operators so the
verifier downstream catches the mismatch.

Mapping table:
  HIR_OP_ADD (1)  -> MIR_ADD  (20002)
  HIR_OP_SUB (2)  -> MIR_SUB  (20003)
  HIR_OP_MUL (3)  -> MIR_MUL  (20004)
  HIR_OP_DIV (4)  -> MIR_DIV  (20005)
  HIR_OP_MOD (5)  -> MIR_MOD  (20006)
  HIR_OP_EQ  (10) -> MIR_EQ   (20100)
  HIR_OP_NE  (11) -> MIR_NE   (20101)
  HIR_OP_LT  (12) -> MIR_LT   (20102)
  HIR_OP_LE  (13) -> MIR_LE   (20103)
  HIR_OP_GT  (14) -> MIR_GT   (20104)
  HIR_OP_GE  (15) -> MIR_GE   (20105)
  HIR_OP_AND (20) -> MIR_AND  (20010)
  HIR_OP_OR  (21) -> MIR_OR   (20011)
  HIR_OP_XOR (22) -> MIR_XOR  (20012)
  HIR_OP_SHL (23) -> MIR_SHL  (20014)
  HIR_OP_SHR (24) -> MIR_SHR  (20015)
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Called once per binary expression at lowering time. The if-cascade
predicts well on hot operators (add, sub, eq) — modern branch
predictors handle the ~16-entry chain in under a cycle on average.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns MIR_NOP for unknown operators rather than silently picking a
plausible-looking opcode; the verifier rejects MIR_NOP in operator
contexts so the failure is visible at integration time.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "map_binary_operator_to_mir_opcode" that takes hir_operator as Integer returns Integer:
    If hir_operator is equal to 1:
        Return 20002
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 2:
        Return 20003
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 3:
        Return 20004
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 4:
        Return 20005
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 5:
        Return 20006
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 10:
        Return 20100
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 11:
        Return 20101
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 12:
        Return 20102
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 13:
        Return 20103
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 14:
        Return 20104
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 15:
        Return 20105
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 20:
        Return 20010
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 21:
        Return 20011
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 22:
        Return 20012
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 23:
        Return 20014
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 24:
        Return 20015
    End If

    Note: Canonical operator encoding produced by the parser/AST and carried
    Note: through HIR (binary_expr offset 24): the lexer TOKEN type for the
    Note: operator (e.g. TOKEN_PLUS = 500), NOT the legacy 1..24 mini-encoding
    Note: above. lower_hir_binary_expression_post reads ast_node@80 -> hir@24 and
    Note: passes it here verbatim, so the real input is the token code. Map every
    Note: binary operator token to its MIR opcode; an unmapped operator falls
    Note: through to MIR_NOP (which the backend silently drops), so this table
    Note: must stay complete. (See compiler/frontend/lexical/token_constants.runa
    Note: for the token values and mir.runa for the MIR opcode values.)
    Note: Arithmetic.
    If hir_operator is equal to 500:
        Return 20002
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 501:
        Return 20003
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 502:
        Return 20004
    End If
    Note: TOKEN_MULTIPLIED (393) — the word form `multiplied by`.
    If hir_operator is equal to 393:
        Return 20004
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 503:
        Return 20005
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 394:
        Return 20005
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 504:
        Return 20006
    End If
    Note: Comparisons (symbol and word forms).
    If hir_operator is equal to 510:
        Return 20100
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 400:
        Return 20100
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 511:
        Return 20101
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 512:
        Return 20102
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 402:
        Return 20102
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 514:
        Return 20103
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 513:
        Return 20104
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 401:
        Return 20104
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 515:
        Return 20105
    End If
    Note: Bitwise and shifts.
    If hir_operator is equal to 530:
        Return 20010
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 531:
        Return 20011
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 532:
        Return 20012
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 303:
        Return 20012
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 534:
        Return 20014
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 535:
        Return 20015
    End If
    Note: Logical and/or over boolean operands lower to bitwise AND/OR (operands
    Note: are 0/1; short-circuit evaluation for side-effecting operands is handled
    Note: by the control-flow lowering path, not this value-producing binop).
    If hir_operator is equal to 380:
        Return 20010
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 381:
        Return 20011
    End If

    Return 20000
End Process

@Reasoning
Maps a HIR unary operator id to the corresponding MIR opcode.
Companion to map_binary_operator_to_mir_opcode for unary nodes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
HIR_OP_NEG (1) -> MIR_NEG (20007)
HIR_OP_NOT (2) -> MIR_NOT (20013)
Returns MIR_NOP for unrecognised operators.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two-entry if-cascade; predicts perfectly.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Unknown-operator path returns MIR_NOP for explicit verifier
rejection.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "map_unary_operator_to_mir_opcode" that takes hir_operator as Integer returns Integer:
    If hir_operator is equal to 1:
        Return 20007
    End If
    If hir_operator is equal to 2:
        Return 20013
    End If
    Return 20000
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: HIR_LITERAL post handler
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
HIR_LITERAL post: emits a MIR_CONST instruction whose result value
id is freshly allocated and whose constant_value is read directly
from the HIR literal node. Pushes the result value id onto the
result stack for the parent's consumption.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Look up the builder context via the lowering context.
2. Allocate a fresh MIR temp value via allocate_temp_value.
3. Read the literal value at HIR_LITERAL offset 8 (per hir.runa
   layout).
4. Read the literal type at offset 16 if present (0 for untyped).
5. Create a MIR_CONST node via create_mir_const with the value, type,
   is_string=0, string_ptr=0 (string literals carry their string at
   the HIR layer via a separate pathway; non-string literals here
   use the integer/float scalar slot).
6. Emit the instruction via emit_instruction.
7. Push the result value id onto the result stack.
Returns 1 on success.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Hot path — every literal in the program lowers through this proc.
The constant node allocation dominates; future arena allocation for
short-lived const nodes will cut the cost.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Defensive null checks on ctx, builder_ctx, hir_node. A null literal
value or type is treated as a valid 0 (true zero literals are
common).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lower_hir_literal_post" that takes ctx as Integer, hir_node_ptr as Integer, node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    If ctx is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If hir_node_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let builder_ctx be proc lowering_get_builder_ctx from LCtx with ctx
    If builder_ctx is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let result_value be proc allocate_temp_value from MIRBuilder with builder_ctx
    Let literal_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_node_ptr, 8
    Let literal_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_node_ptr, 16

    Note: Detect string-class literals via the HIR_LITERAL value_type tag at
    Note: offset 48 (set by hir_builder.lower_literal from the AST literal-class
    Note: token type). Token 100 = TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL, 101 = TOKEN_RAW_STRING_LITERAL;
    Note: both carry a raw char* lexeme pointer in the value slot (mirrored at
    Note: offset 8). String literals must lower to a relocatable .rodata entry, NOT
    Note: a baked absolute immediate, so flag the const node as a string and carry
    Note: its content pointer in string_ptr. The pointer is read again ONLY at
    Note: emit time to write the .string directive. Non-string literals keep the
    Note: numeric immediate path (is_string=0, string_ptr=0).
    Let value_kind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_node_ptr, 48
    Let is_string be 0
    Let string_ptr be 0
    If value_kind is equal to 100:
        Set is_string to 1
        Set string_ptr to literal_value
    End If
    If value_kind is equal to 101:
        Set is_string to 1
        Set string_ptr to literal_value
    End If

    Let const_inst be proc create_mir_const from MIRNodes with result_value, literal_value, literal_type, is_string, string_ptr
    If const_inst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc emit_instruction from MIRBuilder with builder_ctx, const_inst
    proc lowering_push_result from LCtx with ctx, result_value
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: HIR_IDENTIFIER post handler
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
HIR_IDENTIFIER post: looks up the previously-mapped MIR value id
for the identifier's resolved symbol id. The map was populated when
the identifier's defining HIR_LET_STATEMENT (or parameter binding)
was lowered. Pushes the looked-up value onto the result stack.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Read HIR identifier id at HIR_IDENTIFIER offset 16.
2. Call lookup_mir_value to find the corresponding MIR value id.
3. If lookup returns 0 (undefined), record an error and return 0.
4. Push the value id onto the result stack.
Returns 1 on success.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) dictionary lookup via the MIR builder's value map.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Undefined-identifier path sets the error flag and stops traversal
so the driver doesn't emit incomplete MIR.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lower_hir_identifier_post" that takes ctx as Integer, hir_node_ptr as Integer, node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    If ctx is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If hir_node_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let builder_ctx be proc lowering_get_builder_ctx from LCtx with ctx
    If builder_ctx is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_node_ptr, 16
    Let mir_value be proc lookup_mir_value from MIRBuilder with builder_ctx, hir_id

    Note:
    Module-global read. A mutable top-level Let has no alloca mapping (the define
    handler registered it as a global instead), so lookup_mir_value misses. If the
    HIR symbol id names a registered global, materialise its address with a
    function-local MIR_GLOBAL_ADDR (`leaq <name>(%rip), <reg>`) and LOAD through it,
    so this read observes whatever the most recent Set stored — the cross-procedure
    behaviour the monolith provides via leaq name(%rip)/movq (reg). This is checked
    BEFORE the callee/error fallbacks: a global identifier is a genuine value, not
    an unresolved symbol.
    :End Note
    If mir_value is equal to 0:
        Let global_name be proc mir_context_lookup_global from MIRBuilder with builder_ctx, hir_id
        If global_name is not equal to 0:
            Let g_addr_value be proc allocate_temp_value from MIRBuilder with builder_ctx
            Let g_addr_inst be proc create_mir_global_addr from MIRNodes with g_addr_value, global_name, 8
            If g_addr_inst is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            proc emit_instruction from MIRBuilder with builder_ctx, g_addr_inst

            Let g_loaded_value be proc allocate_temp_value from MIRBuilder with builder_ctx
            Let g_load_inst be proc create_mir_load from MIRNodes with g_loaded_value, g_addr_value, 0, 0, 0
            If g_load_inst is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            proc emit_instruction from MIRBuilder with builder_ctx, g_load_inst
            proc lowering_push_result from LCtx with ctx, g_loaded_value
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If mir_value is equal to 0:
        Note: A bare identifier with no MIR value mapping while lowering a
        Note: call's callee child (callee_depth > 0) names a top-level function
        Note: rather than a local variable. The direct-call path in
        Note: lower_hir_call_expression_post resolves such callees by NAME and
        Note: discards this pushed value, so emit a benign sentinel (0) and
        Note: succeed instead of failing symbol resolution at the MIR layer.
        Note: Outside callee context an unmapped identifier is a genuine
        Note: lowering error.
        Let in_callee be proc lowering_in_callee from LCtx with ctx
        If in_callee is equal to 1:
            proc lowering_push_result from LCtx with ctx, 0
            Return 1
        End If
        proc lowering_set_error from LCtx with ctx, 1, hir_node_ptr
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: A local variable / parameter is backed by an alloca (see the
    Note: HIR_LET_STATEMENT and process-parameter lowering, which map the
    Note: symbol id to its alloca via map_hir_to_mir_value). lookup_mir_value
    Note: therefore returns the alloca's value id, which is the ADDRESS of the
    Note: variable's storage slot, not its current value. Reading the variable
    Note: in value context must LOAD from that address; pushing the alloca id
    Note: directly makes every use of the variable (e.g. `Return x`,
    Note: `x plus 1`) operate on the stack-slot pointer instead of the stored
    Note: value. The store/assignment path consumes the variable as an lvalue
    Note: through its own handler (it looks up the alloca id directly), so it is
    Note: unaffected by this rvalue load.
    Let loaded_value be proc allocate_temp_value from MIRBuilder with builder_ctx
    Let load_inst be proc create_mir_load from MIRNodes with loaded_value, mir_value, 0, 0, 0
    If load_inst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc emit_instruction from MIRBuilder with builder_ctx, load_inst
    proc lowering_push_result from LCtx with ctx, loaded_value
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: HIR_BINARY_EXPRESSION post handler
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
HIR_BINARY_EXPRESSION post: consumes two child results from the
stack (right first, then left, matching the visitor's child-index
order: 0=left, 1=right, with the LIFO stack returning the most
recently pushed first). Emits the MIR binary op and pushes the
result.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Read the operator id at HIR_BINARY_EXPRESSION offset 24.
2. Pop right operand value id (most recent push from child_index 1).
3. Pop left operand value id (push from child_index 0).
4. Map the operator id to a MIR opcode.
5. Allocate a fresh result value id.
6. Create the MIR binary op and emit it.
7. Push the result.
Returns 1 on success.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Hot path. Two pops, one push, one opcode mapping, one node
allocation.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
If either pop returns 0 (empty stack or null context), the handler
records an error and stops.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lower_hir_binary_expression_post" that takes ctx as Integer, hir_node_ptr as Integer, node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    If ctx is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If hir_node_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let builder_ctx be proc lowering_get_builder_ctx from LCtx with ctx
    If builder_ctx is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let operator be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_node_ptr, 24
    Let result_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_node_ptr, 32

    Let right_value be proc lowering_pop_result from LCtx with ctx
    Let left_value be proc lowering_pop_result from LCtx with ctx

    If left_value is equal to 0:
        proc lowering_set_error from LCtx with ctx, 2, hir_node_ptr
        Return 0
    End If
    If right_value is equal to 0:
        proc lowering_set_error from LCtx with ctx, 3, hir_node_ptr
        Return 0
    End If

    Let mir_opcode be proc map_binary_operator_to_mir_opcode with operator
    Let result_value be proc allocate_temp_value from MIRBuilder with builder_ctx

    Let binary_inst be proc create_mir_binary_op from MIRNodes with mir_opcode, result_value, left_value, right_value, result_type
    If binary_inst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc emit_instruction from MIRBuilder with builder_ctx, binary_inst
    proc lowering_push_result from LCtx with ctx, result_value
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: HIR_UNARY_EXPRESSION post handler
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
HIR_UNARY_EXPRESSION post: consumes the single operand result,
emits the MIR unary op, and pushes the result.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Read operator id at offset 24, result type at offset 32.
2. Pop operand value id from the result stack.
3. Map operator to MIR opcode and allocate result value.
4. Create + emit MIR unary node.
5. Push result.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Single pop, single push.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Empty-stack pop is treated as a lowering error.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lower_hir_unary_expression_post" that takes ctx as Integer, hir_node_ptr as Integer, node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    If ctx is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If hir_node_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let builder_ctx be proc lowering_get_builder_ctx from LCtx with ctx
    If builder_ctx is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let operator be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_node_ptr, 24
    Let result_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_node_ptr, 32

    Let operand_value be proc lowering_pop_result from LCtx with ctx
    If operand_value is equal to 0:
        proc lowering_set_error from LCtx with ctx, 4, hir_node_ptr
        Return 0
    End If

    Let mir_opcode be proc map_unary_operator_to_mir_opcode with operator
    Let result_value be proc allocate_temp_value from MIRBuilder with builder_ctx

    Let unary_inst be proc create_mir_unary_op from MIRNodes with mir_opcode, result_value, operand_value, result_type
    If unary_inst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc emit_instruction from MIRBuilder with builder_ctx, unary_inst
    proc lowering_push_result from LCtx with ctx, result_value
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION pre + post handlers
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION uses a pre handler to record the argument count
target (read from the HIR node's arg_count field at offset 24) into
the pending_lvalue slot. The post handler pops exactly that many
argument MIR values (plus the callee at child_index 0) and emits
the MIR_CALL.

Recording the count up-front rather than relying on the result
stack's depth makes the implementation robust against expression
subnodes that push but don't pop (none in current HIR but a
defensive design choice).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Pre: read arg_count at HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION offset 24; store via
lowering_set_pending_lvalue (we reuse the pending_lvalue slot for
this purpose since Set-statement is the only other client and
Set-pre/Call-pre never nest in a way that would conflict — Set is
a statement, Call is an expression).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Cold compared to the post handler. Single int64 read and write.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Defensive: arg_count of 0 is a valid no-args call.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lower_hir_call_expression_pre" that takes ctx as Integer, hir_node_ptr as Integer, node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    If ctx is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If hir_node_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: No pre-handler state is needed: the post handler recovers this call's
    Note: argument count directly from the static HIR node (offset 24), which is
    Note: nesting-immune. (A former pre/post scratch slot was overwritten by an
    Note: inner call in `f(a, g(b))`, making the outer call lower with zero args.)
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION child-enter: the callee is child_index 0 (the HIR
visitor visits callee before arguments). A direct call's callee names a
top-level function that has no MIR value mapping, so it must NOT be lowered
as an ordinary value-context identifier (which would force a variable load
and fail symbol lookup). Raising callee_depth around the callee child makes
the identifier post handler treat an unmapped callee name as a benign
reference rather than an error. Arguments (child_index >= 1) are normal
value-context expressions and are lowered without the flag.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
On child_index 0, increment callee_depth via lowering_enter_callee. Other
child indices are left untouched. Always returns 1 (continue traversal).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One field op on the callee child only; no-op for argument children.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Balanced with the child-exit handler so the flag is cleared even when the
callee is the only child.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lower_hir_call_expression_child_enter" that takes ctx as Integer, parent_node as Integer, parent_node_type as Integer, child_index as Integer returns Integer:
    If ctx is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If child_index is equal to 0:
        proc lowering_enter_callee from LCtx with ctx
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION child-exit: clears the callee-context flag once the
callee child (child_index 0) has been fully lowered, so the argument
children that follow are lowered in ordinary value context.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
On child_index 0, decrement callee_depth via lowering_exit_callee. Always
returns 1.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One field op on the callee child only.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pairs with child-enter; lowering_exit_callee floors the depth at 0.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lower_hir_call_expression_child_exit" that takes ctx as Integer, parent_node as Integer, parent_node_type as Integer, child_index as Integer returns Integer:
    If ctx is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If child_index is equal to 0:
        proc lowering_exit_callee from LCtx with ctx
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION post: consumes the callee and N argument MIR
values from the result stack and emits a MIR_CALL. Argument order
on the stack is reversed (the LIFO stack returns most-recent first)
so we pop into a List in reverse and pass that to create_mir_call.
The FFI metadata (callee_is_external, callee_convention_id) is
propagated from the per-builder externals registry per P2-D.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Recover the recorded arg_count via lowering_take_pending_lvalue.
2. Build a List of N arguments by popping N values and inserting at
   the head of the list (so source order is preserved).
3. Pop the callee value id (which was child_index 0, pushed first
   so popped after all args).
4. Read the return type at offset 32 of the HIR node.
5. Read the callee name string pointer at offset 8 of the HIR node
   (the original HIR identifier text); look it up in the per-
   builder externals registry.
6. Allocate a result value id and create the MIR_CALL.
7. If the callee resolves to a registered external, propagate the
   FFI metadata.
8. Emit and push the result.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Hot path for any program with function calls. Cost dominated by the
two list operations (build + walk) — both O(N) in arg_count.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Defensive: missing callee or arguments are treated as lowering
errors. The pending_lvalue is always cleared.
@End Security_Scope

