Note: ============================================================
Note: HIR_INTERPOLATED_STRING post handler (10009)
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
HIR_INTERPOLATED_STRING post: lowers a string interpolation expr
to a chain of MIR_CALLs to the runtime string concatenation
helper. The visitor will not auto-walk the segment list; this
handler consumes from the HIR node directly the count of segments
and pops that many MIR values from the result stack (those pushed
by the visitor's recursion into each interpolated expression
segment, if such recursion exists; otherwise the segments are
emitted inline by reading their literal payload here).

For the foundation pipeline we emit a single MIR_CALL to a runtime
"string_concat" intrinsic taking the count and a list of value ids.
The value-id list is allocated on the heap and freed after the
call is constructed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Read segment_count at HIR_INTERPOLATED_STRING offset 16.
2. Read segments_list at offset 8 (a List of segment HIR pointers
   whose MIR values were pushed by their own post handlers, if any).
3. Pop segment_count values off the stack into a List in source
   order (LIFO reversal via head-insert).
4. Read interpolation_type at offset 24.
5. Allocate a result value, build a MIR_CALL to the string concat
   runtime helper (callee value id of 0 marks an intrinsic; LIR
   resolves it to the runtime symbol).
6. Push result.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One call emission per interpolation. Argument-list construction
is O(N) in segment count.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Defensive: zero segments produces an empty-string constant rather
than a zero-arg call.
@End Security_Scope

