Note: ============================================================
Note: HIR_FUNCTION_POINTER post handler (10017)
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
HIR_FUNCTION_POINTER post: lowers a function-pointer expression to the
RIP-relative ADDRESS of the named function, exactly as the monolith oracle
does (`leaq <label>(%rip), %rax` in codegen_generate_variable_expr's symbol-
reference fallthrough and its EXPR_FUNCTION_POINTER arm). The node is produced
both by the `$name` literal and by lower_identifier when a function name with
one or more parameters is used as a value (a callback/handler argument such as
`lowering_pre_trampoline from LCtx`). The function's link LABEL is carried as a
ready-to-emit string in the node's function_name slot (offset 8): lower_identifier
stamps the MODULE-MANGLED label there so the address materialized here matches
the symbol the function's own definition emits across separately-compiled objects.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Read the function label string at HIR_FUNCTION_POINTER offset 8.
2. Allocate a result value and emit MIR_GLOBAL_ADDR(label) -- the same
   instruction the mutable-global read path uses, lowered to
   `leaq <label>(%rip), <reg>` by the x86-64 backend. The pointer width is 8.
3. Push the result (the function address) onto the result stack.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Single MIR_GLOBAL_ADDR emit per function-pointer reference; cold path.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
A zero function label is a lowering error (HIR construction must have stamped
the label; an unresolved name never reaches here as a function pointer).
@End Security_Scope

